          "body": "The war-horse passage (39:19-25) is the most extended single portrait in the chapter and arguably one of the most celebrated pieces of nature poetry in the Hebrew Bible. John Calvin called it 'incomparable'; the Victorian commentator Samuel Cox described it as the finest description of a horse in all of ancient literature. God devotes seven verses to a creature that is not wild but is also not ultimately under Job's command — its courage, its terror-inducing snort (39:20), its contempt for the quiver and spear (39:22-23), and its ecstatic response to the trumpet (39:24-25) all originate in God's creative endowment, not in Job's breeding or training. The horse laughs at fear (sachaq, the same verb the wild donkey uses for the city, 39:7, and the ostrich uses for its speed, 39:18) — a thread of divine humor runs through the portrait gallery. The war-horse is God's exhibit of creaturely magnificence that serves human purposes (battle) while remaining theologically unintelligible to Job as its source. Job did not give it courage; Job cannot replicate it."
