          "title": "The hawk and the eagle — inaccessible wisdom from above",
          "body": "The chapter's closing movement (39:26-30) shifts the argument skyward. The hawk migrates southward not by Job's understanding (binah, 39:26 — the same word withheld from the ostrich in 39:17); the eagle mounts at God's command, not Job's (39:27). The eagle portrait is architecturally precise: it nests on an inaccessible crag (39:28), sees prey from distances Job cannot match (39:29), and feeds its young on the blood of the slain (39:30). The final verse is the chapter's single declarative statement — after 29 verses of questions, God does not ask: He states. The eagle does not explain itself. The slain are there; the eagle finds them; the young are fed. God's governance of the apex predator is not philosophical; it is concrete, carnivorous, and complete. The creature that lives highest and sees farthest is not accountable to Job for where it builds its nest or what it eats."
